My biggest complaint is that the movie wouldn't just let bad things happen to the main characters. As objectively dumb as it was that Rey suddenly and randomly had the ability of Force lightning, I was nonetheless dumbstruck when I thought she'd killed Chewbacca. But then when it was revealed he was still alive, I groaned out loud in the theater. And that whole thing with C-3PO losing his memory was a fucking waste of time and I didn't even bother getting invested in that plotline because I just KNEW that it would get fixed by the end of the movie. Finally, when Rey stabbed Kylo, I didn't feel bad in the slightest because even a 5-year-old could tell that he was needed for the climax of the film and some stupid Force shit was going to happen to save the day for the script writers.

The Rise of Skywalker had no balls, and the only way I could enjoy it was by turning my brain off and forgetting all about the established lore.

I thought Force Awakens was an okay movie, it was fun and entertaining, nothing special but an enjoyable experience...

Many will disagree...but I think Last Jedi is great, i like everything they done with Luke. This movie made me way more invested in Rey's relationship with Kylo Ren. Imo all the major characters introduced in Ep VII were improved upon. Many great moments, such as Luke's last stand, Yoda's return, and Luke's death in front of the twin suns was really moving...

So im positive on Ep VII and VIII...but this movie sucks sweaty gun gun balls...

Im not mad at Ep 9...im just disappointed...

This movie felt so weird to watch, it felt like i missed a film in between Last Jedi and this one, things just happen for the sake of it...nothing felt like it was set up and nothing gets explained. 

The opening is SO RUSHED and was a giant cluster f*ck, how did Kylo find out that Palpatine was alive?! How did Rey, Finn, and Poe become like a group of close friends? This is what I mean by i felt like there was a film missing in between this one and the last one, it's like the set up was done off screen and they skip straight to the 'pay off' . It felt like the movie started in the middle of another one that was supposed to exsist in between this and TLJ...it's so bizarre...

Also they don't even bother explaining Palpatine's presence in a convincing way...could u imagine the people who went into this movie completely blind without watching any trailers and don't even know that Palpatine is in it, could u imagine how baffled they would be when they see that Palpatine just appears at the very start with little to no realistic or convincing explanation, it would be the most confusing sh*t ever, and what makes it worse is that Palpatine's appearance feels completely pointless and a desperate attempt to get people who didn't like TLJ somewhat interested again...

This movie is just complete nonsense...it seriously felt like a continuation of a movie that never exsisted, it's so f*cking weird...and just feels completely disjointed from the last 2 films.

The plot twist of Rey being the grand daughter of Palpatine is laughbly bad... like WTF! I mean sure it was unexpected...but that doesn't mean it's good...it's probably one of the WORST plot twists i've seen in a film...PERIOD...and makes her arc and development from the last movie completely pointless and just completely ruins what made me like about her character in the last film. Basically:

Rian Johnson: Anybody can be a hero...u don't have to be from a special bloodline to be someone special or someone of importance...u can build and create yr own legacy...who yr related to doesn't matter...it's who u choose to be that matters...

JJ Abrams: NOOOOOO! U MUST BE RELATED TO SOMEONE IMPORTANT...OTHERWISE U WILL NEVER BE IMPORTANT!

Like wtf man...

It makes TLJ feel completely pointless and just bashes that film, the film with actual interesting ideas and story, while this film feels like fan fiction created by someone on Reddit...how was this approved to be released?! It's bashing of the last film isn't subtle, it completely retconnes or goes against what Rian did in his film, Rey comes from a family of nobody's, nah she's actually a descendant of Palpatine. Luke catching the lightsaber and saying 'A jedi's weapon deserves more respect' felt like it was mocking Luke's characterization in TLJ......lightsabers aren't what make a jedi special, it's they're knowledge and wisdom of THE FORCE that does...a lightsaber is just a weapon they use...it's not the core of what makes a great jedi...Luke's knowledge of the force is what gave him the victory against Kylo in the last jedi not a lightsaber...in this he acts like the lightsaber is what makes the jedi...it's so frustrating. Snoke simply being used to progress and push Rey's and Kylo's story foward...nah...he was just Palpatine's puppet all along...because idk f*ck it why not, just put a bunch of meaningless twists that mean nothing...and just completely rush the story...this movie literally goes against everything i liked about TLJ, a movie that doesn't rely on nostalgia, a film that challenges it's audience rather than cater to them, and has actual themes in it's story, it's a movie that has something to say...this is the opposite...

Kylo's death felt so sudden and out of nowhere...and u do it right after Rey kisses him...because that ain't so cliche, i was actually for Kylo and Rey having romance or 'Reylo' as many fans call it...a hero and villian having romantic feelings towards each other would've been an interesting story...but it was done in the worst way possible and was really rushed...

Now i will admit there were some good moments in this mess of a movie, like Alex said seeing Chewbacca's reaction to Leia's death was heartbreaking. C3-PO was actually really entertaining in this, id say it's probably the character at it's best in this film. The confrontations between Kylo Ren and Rey were pretty good and by far the best and entertaining parts of the film...(except for the one where Rey is revealed to be a Palpatine). Luke and Leia finally being together again at the end was a nice and heart warming moment...this movie definitely has it's moments...but overall i think this is a really BAD and disappointing conclusion to this series...but atleast it ain't as bad as the final season of Game of Thrones...😅

I know alot of fans blame TLJ for how this film turned out...and they say how Rian left JJ with nothing to go on...but i disagree...there were many things Abrams could've expanded upon from Rian's ideas...i'll even list things he could've done...

- At the end of TLJ, Kylo Ren is an unstable and emotionally confused boy in charge of an entire army, thats an interesting story right there, that u could've expanded upon, u could've also expanded upon the conflict between Hux and Kylo...like near the end of TLJ Hux was gonna kill Kylo while he was knocked out, and since Kylo started kicking the sh*t out of him, there is a story there. What if Hux and Kylo are constantly at each others throats, what if First Order soldiers lost faith in they're leaders and the army just crumbles due to poor leadership.

- Rian re-united the whole group at the end, Rey was back with Finn and met Poe for the first time, this film could've had Rey, Poe, and Finn build a friendship as a group ON SCREEN, instead of off screen like they did here, i like those characters individually but as a group they're really weak. 

- Rey and Kylo connections could be continued and play a more major part of the story, there wasn't really much of it in this film...and thats what i was most excited to see...it was one of the best parts of the last film...and they don't really do much with it...except for one admittedly cool fight scene...

- You could've actually built up a romantic connection between Rey and kylo instead of forcing in a kiss before Kylo dies...it was so rushed in this film...

- Luke could've had a bigger affect on the plot, he could've taught Rey multiple lessons as the films goes on, instead of having one moment that mocks the last film without any subtlety and one fan servicey moment, because Luke doesn't really teach Rey that much in the film before this, so it would've been cool to see Luke continue Rey's training from the last film...instead of having Leia teach her off screen...

There are other directions u could've taken this in...directions better than this atleast...

This movie ain't in my headcanon, to me TLJ is the last film, Luke inspiring hope across the galaxy with his last stand is a better ending to the series than this...Luke dies in TLJ and thats where the Skywalker saga ends for me...Luke's story ends in that film which means the saga ends with that film...

I honestly wish Rian Johnson directed the whole trilogy...i was WAAYYY MORE interested in the story he wanted tell than JJ's...sorry JJ ain't hatin on ya but thats how i feel...

honestly, i felt like this new sequel had so so much potential to be the greatest star wars films ever made. they've got it all- the money, the cast, the audience. unfortunately, the reason why it received as much negative reviews as it did was because of the lack of planning. there wasn't an overall gameplan or a vision/draft which was why the last jedi and rise of skywalker was that underwhelming. it was full of surprises, yes, but it was just a wow factor in the moment, not something that was truly deep and contributed to the trilogy as a whole. for example, to make the resurrection of palpatine more believable, they could've given subtle hints in TFA and TLJ to truly set up for such a big reveal. it was like JJ made TROS without actually watching it. the new sequels relied heavily on thriller and nostalgia/emotion. don't get me wrong, i enjoyed the new sequels, but the only way to truly enjoy is it to look past the old movies and accept it for the way it is, and its hard for the star wars fans who've been following the saga for years as most people see this as a continuation of the old.

the second issue was the writing. as i said, they focused heavily on thriller, for example including scenes like the casino adventure on TLJ, bits of humor tossed here and there and nostalgic scenes which was entirely pointless.

the third issue was the characters! in my opinion, they had really great ideas and i can see what they were trying to achieve with the new generation of legends and heroes, but the lack of depth(besides kylo ren) made finn, poe, and rey especially look plain and basic. if only they added more scenes of reys character development rather than show more scenes of her heroically saving the day. that's the difference with rey and kylo ren. with kylo ren, we got the chance to look at his conflicts, inner struggles and thoughts (which was brilliantly displayed by subtle body language) and what prompted him to do what he did, making kylo ren a more relatable and realistic character. TLJ did an amazing job displaying kylo ren's character arc by putting him in high pressure situations and making him constantly battle with the decision of being with the light and dark sides. rey however, was thoroughly underdeveloped. she had good motives and intentions, but no reasons why besides being in the light side of the force. she had the skill, but no scenes to show her struggles of acquiring it; no emotional trauma or experiences which was what made her look like a 'mary sue' ( i personally don't agree with that if you look deeper, but on the surface.)

overall, what i can say about the new sequels is that it lacks the lustre of the old movies, but is unique and bold in its own way that made me crave for more. for me, compared to the old movies the story isn't as well told and put but it was filled with action and thriller in a way that made you sit down and watch the whole movie with your eyes glued to the screen for the entire duration. overall, the new sequels is good--if you dismiss expectations and accept it the way it is.

After having seen your video fully, I have to say that you've won back my respect. It's not because of you criticizing something I also find many problems with, but because you're adhering to the standards that you always apply to your criticisms, which were absent when you were previously talking about The Last Jedi.

For me, TFA was just ok. I think I ranked it my 5th favorite out of the 7 main films, but over time, I can't. It's my favorite out of the ST, but that puts it at #7 for me. I only ever watched it once. It had me wondering why people were praising it as the "be all to end all" SW film. That was even without noticing all of the ways in which it ripped off of A New Hope, but I definitely noticed a lot of them.

TLJ, on the other hand... I'll say that you're right about it as a standalone. The main problem people have with the film is that it doesn't respect any of what came before it, and as a result forms many contradictions and retcons (such as how hyperspace travel works, or how the Force now just balances itself, etc.). If we don't take into account the fact that it's part of a series/universe that it has to respect, a lot (not all) of those issues disappear, and it can be seen as a more fun movie to people. But since most people watching it are big-time Star Wars fans, how it fits in with the rest of the story really matters.

It's kind of like Looper. When you break it down, there's actually a lot in the movie that doesn't make sense or work at all. YMS did such a breakdown, but at the same time he said he really liked the movie and it was really fun, and I agree. If TLJ didn't have to adhere to the laws and such of the previous films/stories, I'd put it in the same boat. It actually becomes a lot more fun of a movie to watch if you don't regard it as canon (since if you do, it breaks the SW universe anyway).

Hell, I'd even say it has some really good/interesting ideas (Rey and Kylo having a thing together, as a Jedi and Sith on opposite sides, or Luke falling from grace, etc.). It just didn't work at earning them and/or execute them very well. It had a lot of ideas that I'd have been down for if they'd been written and planned with more care. Luke could very well have had such a drastic change in character, but we'd have to experience it. What we got was him suddenly having a complete 180 shift in character, without doing anything to earn it, and telling us "This is how it is now. Done.". It'd be like if we start out with Phantom Menace and the next movie skipped straight to A New Hope. How would people have handled that if they went "This is Anakin now. Done."? I definitely wouldn't have felt the weight of validity of the change as much as with the way they showed it.

But to be fair, it's not all Rian's fault. Every Star Wars movie to date has taken place with quite some time between each other (1 year at the shortest, or 3, or 10). JJ ended TFA on a serious cliffhanger that Rian was forced to start off with, meaning that literally no time was able to pass between movies and it basically turned it from its own part of the story to a direct continuation of the first part. Rian wasn't given any kind of time jump to change the scenery, stakes, or situation. It's really hard (or even impossible) to set up anything new in a sequel if it takes place right where the previous movie left off. But Rian tried to. Not to say that he didn't do it poorly on his own, but he was given a tough job to begin with. Then again, he could've started the movie off with Rey meeting Luke, and then a time skip, but how would that work with the opening crawl? Seems like that scene would need to happen first and THEN the crawl, which would've been awkward...


With Rise of Skywalker, you're definitely right about it feeling like a video game. Like I said before, it was trying to set up basically an entirely new story from scratch since Rian Johnson wrapped everything up with the last movie. That was definitely on him. Both he and JJ did the two no-no's that you should never do when making a Star Wars movie, or in Rian's case when making a Star Wars movie that's not the end of a trilogy.


I will give the film that I was already having the feeling that she was Palpatine's granddaughter as far back as TFA, but there's no way they planned for Palpatine to have been alive and behind this from the start. I believe there was even leaked information that contradicts that notion.

Also I wouldn't say you're being overly critical. It's been pretty vastly panned as the worse in the entire saga. Tbh I was excited when I heard Diensey would be taking the reigns of Star Wars. I always loved the prequels, but my excitement was in them continuing the story. I saw how they handled Pirates and thought they were gonna do something to that effect.

I was very wrong.

But to be fair, it's not all Rian's fault. Every Star Wars movie to date has taken place with quite some time between each other (1 year at the shortest, or 3, or 10). JJ ended TFA on a serious cliffhanger that Rian was forced to start off with, meaning that literally no time was able to pass between movies and it basically turned it from its own part of the story to a direct continuation of the first part. Rian wasn't given any kind of time jump to change the scenery, stakes, or situation. It's really hard (or even impossible) to set up anything new in a sequel if it takes place right where the previous movie left off. But Rian tried to. Not to say that he didn't do it poorly on his own, but he was given a tough job to begin with. Then again, he could've started the movie off with Rey meeting Luke, and _then_ a time skip, but how would that work with the opening crawl? Seems like that scene would need to happen first and THEN the crawl, which would've been awkward...


With Rise of Skywalker, you're definitely right about it feeling like a video game. Like I said before, it was trying to set up basically an entirely new story from scratch since Rian Johnson wrapped everything up with the last movie. That was definitely on him. Both he and JJ did the two no-no's that you should never do when making a Star Wars movie, or in Rian's case when making a Star Wars movie that's not the end of a trilogy.


I will give the film that I was already having the feeling that she was Palpatine's granddaughter as far back as TFA, but there's no way they planned for Palpatine to have been alive and behind this from the start. I believe there was even leaked information that contradicts that notion.

Also I wouldn't say you're being overly critical. It's been pretty vastly panned as the worse in the entire saga. Tbh I was excited when I heard Diensey would be taking the reigns of Star Wars. I always loved the prequels, but my excitement was in them continuing the story. I saw how they handled Pirates and thought they were gonna do something to that effect.

I was very wrong.
